did.unittitle: Harrison Lee papers
did.abstract: Collection consists of the D.C. Comprehensive Plan including documents relating to the comprehensive plan for the National Capital; manuscript and committee records; printed ephemera; newspaper articles; newsletters; magazine articles; brochures and guidebooks; awards and certificates. The material dates from 1928-92.

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: Harrison Lee papers, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: In June of 1996, Anna L. Lee donated the papers of her late husband Harrison Lee to the George Washington University (GWU) Gelman Library. All rights and interests were transferred to the Department of Special Collections.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Some material may be copyrighted or restricted. It is the patron's obligation to determine and satisfy copyright or other case restrictions when publishing or otherwise distributing materials found in the collections.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Harrison Lee (1920-1993) worked for the U.S. Army and the CIA as an intelligence analyst. After his retirement in 1973, Lee became an active leader in the Washington, D.C. Chinatown community. The collection material reflects Lee's involvement as a community activist and leader in Washington's Chinatown for more than 20 years. The period covered in this collection coincided with one of the most interesting and active phases of redevelopment and urban planning in the city.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection consists of the D.C. Comprehensive Plan including documents relating to the comprehensive plan for the National Capital; manuscript and committee records; printed ephemera; newspaper articles; newsletters; magazine articles; brochures and guidebooks; awards and certificates. The material dates from 1928-92.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into seven series: D.C. urban planning/ D.C. comprehensive plan, Community and business organizations, Wah Luck House, Miscellaneous/ peripheral projects and concerns of the Chinese Community in Washington, Printed ephemera, Awards and certificates, and Blueprints.

did.unittitle: D.C. urban planning/D.C. comprehensive plan

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of the DC Urban Planning/DC Comprehensive plan. The D.C. Comprehensive Plan was adopted by the D.C. City Council and enacted into law in 1984 after years of full community review and comment. Until the Home Rule Act of 1974, the federal National Capital Planning Commission was the agency responsible for planning for the district. The Home Rule Act gave local planning authority to the city while N.C.P.C. retained an "overlay" authority for the federal functions. The D.C. Comprehensive Plan plotted a 20-year course for the development of the city. The series consists of general information, DC Downtown Development and Chinatown Development. The material dates from 1977-88.

Wah Luck House

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials on the development of the Wah Luck House. The idea for government subsidized housing for Chinatown's residents displaced by the convention center was a concern of the Chinese Consolidated Benevolent Association since the early 1970s. After a long series of grant proposals for development funds and public hearings, the project was finally approved in 1977. This series traces the history of the Wah Luck House from the purchase of the land, through funding, search for an architect, to determining tenant selection. Designed by Alfred Liu in a style termed as "modernism in Chinese dress", it introduced modern Chinese design motifs with red-paneled balconies on the 10 story, 153 unit white apartment building. When Wah Luck house opened in 1982, there were over 1,500 applications. Five years later the waiting list was cut off at 500. It was the last new housing to be built in Chinatown. Material in this series dates from 1977-82.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of printed materials from the 1975-92. Major sources were the Washington Post, the Washington Times, the Washington Business Journal, and the Metro Chinese Journal, published bi-weekly in Cantonese in Silver Spring, Md. The series also includes newsletters from 1976-92, magazine articles from 1982-95, brochures and guidebooks 1974-90's. This includes D.C. Agency brochures (e.g. on Historic Districts, Using Zoning and Land Use Map) as we as government sponsored and commercial guides to Washington, and Chinatown.
